    "summary": "Physicist by education; moved to Silicon Valley for my first job, at IBM.\n\nAt IBM (2005-2009) I did fundamental research at a novel computer memory, build a pulsed laser tool for measurement of magnetic domain wall activity in nanowires. The work was published in PRL, Nature and other journals. The memory came to market as ST-MRAM in 2016.\n\nThen, at WD (2009-2018), worked in nano-physics and material science. Here, at the magnetic heads production site we made 3 million heads per day and my team was responsible for the measurements of a range of physical properties on these heads in the production line. When data grew, I started using AI to make better use of the data and predict yield and performance metrics online in the production line.\n\nIn 2017 I competed in an Artificial Intelligence competition from the Department of Homeland Security (DHS), predicting contraband on airline passengers as they move through the microwave scanners at airports. In that competition I won the second place, and then decided to do something else with this new AI skill.\n\nIn 2018 I joined Atomwise, with the early engineering team of about 10 engineers. With Atomwise we basically pioneered the idea of using AI for drug discovery. The company grew fast and I was heavily involved in every AI project that Atomwise worked on in those years.\n\nBastiaan.Bergman@gmail.com",
